@* try/catch/throw/lock (BENCH n°29, decision 110): the #go handler THROWS inside a try, CATCHES the
   throw (+5), then runs a lock body (+1) -- so each click adds 6. try/catch/finally maps to the JS
   namesake, `throw new Exception(msg)` to `throw new Error(msg)`, and `lock (x) { … }` to a bare block
   (JS is single-threaded, so a lock can never be contended). The click IS the measurement: #count goes
   0 -> 6 -> 12, exactly as Blazor runs the same C#. A CAUGHT throw is faithful; an UNCAUGHT one is the
   disclosed edge (C# surfaces a .NET exception, JS a bare Error) and is NOT what this app measures. *@

<p>Count: <span id="count">@count</span></p>

<button id="go" @onclick="Go">go</button>

@code {
    private int count = 0;

    private void Go()
    {
        try
        {
            throw new System.Exception("boom");
        }
        catch
        {
            count = count + 5;
        }
        lock (this)
        {
            count = count + 1;
        }
    }
}
